Preliminary Analysis¶

In [6]:
# Provide a brief description of each column
column_description = []
for column in titanic_data.columns:
    dtype = titanic_data[column].dtype
    num_unique = titanic_data[column].nunique()

    if dtype == 'object':
        column_description.append(f"{column}: {dtype} - {num_unique} unique values")
    else:
        mean = titanic_data[column].mean()
        std = titanic_data[column].std()
        column_description.append(f"{column}: {dtype} - {num_unique} unique values, Mean: {mean:.2f}, Std: {std:.2f}")

# Display column descriptions
for desc in column_description:
    print(desc)

Convert Relevant Columns to NumPy Arrays¶

In [7]:
# Convert relevant columns to NumPy arrays
age_array = titanic_data['Age'].to_numpy()
fare_array = titanic_data['Fare'].to_numpy()

Compute Mean, Median, and Standard Deviation¶

In [8]:
# Compute mean, median, and standard deviation using NumPy
age_mean = np.mean(age_array)
age_median = np.median(age_array)
age_std = np.std(age_array)

fare_mean = np.mean(fare_array)
fare_median = np.median(fare_array)
fare_std = np.std(fare_array)

# Display results
print(f"Age - Mean: {age_mean:.2f}, Median: {age_median:.2f}, Std Dev: {age_std:.2f}")
print(f"Fare - Mean: {fare_mean:.2f}, Median: {fare_median:.2f}, Std Dev: {fare_std:.2f}")

Age - Mean: 29.47, Median: 28.00, Std Dev: 14.11
Fare - Mean: 32.31, Median: 14.45, Std Dev: 49.75

Advanced Questions¶

In [15]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

Fit a Simple Linear Regression Model¶

In [16]:
# Choose two numerical columns for linear regression (you can modify this)
predictor_col = 'Age'
target_col = 'Fare'

# Extract predictor and target arrays
X = titanic_data[[predictor_col]].values
y = titanic_data[target_col].values

# Initialize and fit the linear regression model
regressor = LinearRegression()
regressor.fit(X, y)

# Visualize the regression line
plt.scatter(X, y, color='blue')
plt.plot(X, regressor.predict(X), color='red')
plt.title(f"Linear Regression: {target_col.capitalize()} vs. {predictor_col.capitalize()}")
plt.xlabel(predictor_col.capitalize())
plt.ylabel(target_col.capitalize())
plt.show()

# Comment on the fit of the model
print(f"Coefficient: {regressor.coef_[0]:.2f}")
print(f"Intercept: {regressor.intercept_:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared: {regressor.score(X, y):.2f}")

Coefficient: 0.40
Intercept: 20.64
R-squared: 0.01

Group Data and Calculate Mean and Standard Deviation¶

In [17]:
# Choose a categorical column for grouping (you can modify this)
group_col = 'Sex'

# Group the data and calculate mean and standard deviation
grouped_data = titanic_data.groupby(group_col).agg({'Age': ['mean', 'std'],
                                                    'Fare': ['mean', 'std']})

# Rename the columns for clarity
grouped_data.columns = [f'{group_col.capitalize()} Mean Age', f'{group_col.capitalize()} Std Age',
                        f'{group_col.capitalize()} Mean Fare', f'{group_col.capitalize()} Std Fare']

# Display the grouped data
print(grouped_data)
